		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						) Solus Mercurius habet Quodlibetum ingenij,
						Lingua[e], Manus.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Only Mercury has the subtlety [quodlibet] of talent, tongue, and hand.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						( Virtus non queritur de Fortuna. )
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Virtue does not complain about Fortune.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						( Quod facturus eris, dicere sustuleris. Ausonius.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Ausonius"/> 
					<X-ref book_title="Epigrammata de diversis rebus" language="LA" person="Ausonius" text="Quod facturus eris, dicere sustuleris"/>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				"Refrain from saying what you will do." Ausonius.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nusq[uam] ha[e]ret Trismegisti Quodlibetum.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Hermes Trismegistus"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The subtlety of Trismegistus never stays fixed.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Plurimus vsus facetiarum in Conuiuijs, et festiuis Colloquijs: in quibus etiam
						delectant Problemata, qualia in Mensa Philosophica: proposita vrbana, qualia in
						4.to Guatij, et 1.o Castilionis: a[e]nigmata, vulgo <!--JG: Perhaps better to transcribe [quarto] and [primo]-->
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Stefano Guazzo"/>
					<person name="Castiglione"/>
					<book title="Mensa philosophica"/>
					<book title="The civil conversation"/>
					<book title="Book of the Courtier"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<language ident="EN">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						riddles.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				There are many uses for jokes at dinner parties or festive gatherings, where even problems
				are delightful, such as those found in the Mensa Philsophia; otherwise, there are urbane propositions, 
				such as those in the fourth book of Guazzi, and the first book of Castiglione; else puzzles, and riddles in the vernacular. 
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia book_id="FolgersHa2" hand="Italian" id="Ha2.051v_0001" marginalia_continues_to="Ha2.052r_0001" marginalia_to_transcription="Ha2.05r.xml">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Dexterrimi ingenij est, et pra[e]gnantiss[im]a[e] 
						facultatis pragmatica[e], conuertere lecta [p. 423: omnia, antiqua, et neoterica, ad pra[e]sentes personas, res ante oculas positas, et
						instantes Occasiones. Atq[ue] ità ex alienis facere tua: ex veteribus, noua.]
						<!-- Continues onto facing page, left margin, Ha2.052r  -->
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Those most skillful in natural talent, and with the faculty of a most pregnant pragmaticism, transform [all] their readings [p. 423: , whether ancient or modern, for people present today, placing those things before your eyes, and 
				in present circumstances. And so they make foreign things yours, and old things new.]
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
